    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-20T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-20T04:00:00-05:00" n="392"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d392">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A14/685: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in France</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Marriner</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Paris</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-20T10:00:00+01:00"
                            >July 20, 1934—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 20—7:42 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>539. Department’s 293, July 18, 6 p.m.<note n="28" xml:id="d392fn28">Not
                        printed.</note> I saw Massigli<note n="29" xml:id="d392fn29">Assistant
                        Director of Political Affairs, French Foreign Office.</note> yesterday
                    afternoon who said that with respect to first part of the reservation France had
                    no objection either as to matter or form. As to the second part concerning the
                    Persian Gulf although they felt that the matter was irrelevant they had no
                    objection to its basic meaning but on legal grounds felt that it would be
                    necessary for France as the depositary of the ratifications of the treaty to
                    obtain the consent of all the other parties to the treaty to this reservation.
                    He likewise feared that the just consideration of special reservations of this
                    kind might induce a great variety of reservations on the part of other
                    powers.</p>
                <p>He was sorry that Barthou’s<note n="30" xml:id="d392fn30">French Minister for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> absence in England and subsequently in the south of
                    France had delayed this informal answer.</p>
                <p>Copies to London and Geneva.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Marriner</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
